DEEP-seq microfluidic chip fabrication

1.	Introduction
The Valve-seq platform integrates fluorescence-activated identification and microvalve control to enable targeted cell sorting and paired co-encapsulation with barcoded microbeads into droplets. This protocol details the microfluidic chip fabrication process, sample preparation, instrument operation, and library construction.

2.	Microfluidic chip fabrication
The fabrication of the Valve-seq chip was developed by referencing the established methods from the Quake group and incorporating standard PDMS-based microfluidic fabrication techniques1–3, with specific modifications to optimize cell encapsulation efficiency.

3.	Multilayer composite silicon mold fabrication
Silicon molds are fabricated via photolithography and utilized for PDMS casting in microfluidic chip manufacturing. The following materials were utilized:

Materials	Catalog Number
4 inch wafer(Yilanmicro, Shuzhou, China)	Y11136
SU-8 3025(MicroChem, KAYAKU, USA)	Y11336
SU-8 2050(MicroChem, KAYAKU, USA)	Y11452
SU-8 2000.5(MicroChem, KAYAKU, USA)	Y11449
AZ4620(AZ Electronic Materials, USA)	Y11529
PDMS(Sylgard 184, Dow Corning, USA)	01673921
Chlorotrimethylsilane(Aladdin, Shanghai, China)	C104813-500ml
5 inch Chrome mask(Jiaodian, Shenzhen, China)	204002
PGMEA(Sigama-Aldrich, Merck, USA)	Y11426
AZ300MIF(AZ Electronic Materials, USA)	Y11256
IPA(Aladdin, Shanghai, China)	Y11378
DI water(ACMEC, Shanghai, China)	AM1000028

Fabrication steps of flow channel wafer mold:
1.	Plasma(PDC-002-HP, Harrick, USA) surface cleaning of silicon wafers(150W 40s).
2.	A SU-8 2000.5 photoresist layer was spin-coated(4000 rpm 30s) onto the silicon wafer using a spin coater(EZ6-S-EN-3, Schwan, Jiangyin, China).
3.	Cross-linking of the SU-8 photoresist was achieved by a 5-second exposure using a mask aligner(MA/BA 6 Gen4, Karl Suss, USA).
4.	Post-exposure bake (PEB) was performed on a hot plate(HP8, ESPEC, Hefei, China) at 95°C for 30 seconds.
5.	A layer of AZ4620 was spin-coated at 1000 rpm for 30 seconds.
6.	Soft bake: Wafer on a hot plate at 110°C for 80 seconds.
7.	Coat: An additional layer of AZ4620 was spin-coated at 1000 rpm for 30 seconds.
8.	Soft bake: Wafer on a hot plate at 115°C for 180 seconds.
9.	Incubation: 30 min.
10.	Exposure: Three consecutive exposures were performed at a dose of 833 mJ/cm² with 10-second intervals between each exposure(Arc-shaped flow channel chrome mask).
11.	Develop: The wafer was developed with AZ 300MIF developer for 11 minutes.
12.	Rinse and dry: The silicon wafer was rinsed with deionized water (DI water), followed by drying with compressed air.
13.	Reflow: The silicon wafer was placed on a hot plate, where the temperature was gradually increased to 180°C and maintained for 3 hours, followed by cooling to ambient temperature under controlled conditions.
14.	Graphical inspection: The height of the silicon mold was measured using a stylus profilometer(Dektak XT, Bruker, USA), followed by 3D contour examination of the patterned structures with a non-contact 3D surface profiler(VR-6000, Keyence, Japan).
15.	Surface cleaning: Plasma surface cleaning of silicon wafers(150W for 40s).
16.	Coat: An layer of SU-8 3025 was spin-coated at 2300 rpm for 30 seconds.
17.	Soft bake: Wafer on a hot plate at 95°C for 14 mins.
18.	Exposure: Exposures were performed at a dose of 240 mj/cm2.
19.	Post bake: The wafer was heated on a hot plate at 65°C for 1 minute, followed by 5 minutes at 95°C.
20.	Develop: Development was performed using PGMEA for 7 minutes.
21.	Rinse and dry: The wafer was sequentially rinsed with isopropyl alcohol (IPA), anhydrous ethanol, and deionized (DI) water for 10 seconds each, followed by blow-drying with compressed air.
22.	Coat: An layer of SU-8 2050 was spin-coated at 1850 rpm for 30 seconds.
23.	Soft bake: The wafer was heated on a hot plate at 65°C for 3 minute, followed by 9 minutes at 95°C.
24.	Exposure: Exposures were performed at a dose of 215 mj/cm2.
25.	Post bake: The wafer was heated on a hot plate at 65°C for 2 minute, followed by 7 minutes at 95°C.
26.	Develop: Development was performed using PGMEA for 7 minutes.
27.	Rinse and dry: The wafer was sequentially rinsed with isopropyl alcohol (IPA), anhydrous ethanol, and deionized (DI) water for 10 seconds each, followed by blow-drying with compressed air.
28.	Graphical inspection: The height of the silicon mold was measured using a stylus profilometer, followed by 3D contour examination of the patterned structures with a non-contact 3D surface profiler.

Fabrication steps of valve control channel wafer mold:
1.	Surface cleaning: Plasma surface cleaning of silicon wafers(150W for 40s).
2.	Coat: An layer of SU-8 3025 was spin-coated at 2500 rpm for 30 seconds.
3.	Soft bake: Wafer on a hot plate at 95°C for 13 mins.
4.	Exposure: Exposures were performed at a dose of 216 mj/cm2.
5.	Post bake: The wafer was heated on a hot plate at 65°C for 1 minute, followed by 4 minutes at 95°C.
6.	Develop: Development was performed using PGMEA for 6.5 minutes.
7.	Rinse and dry: The wafer was sequentially rinsed with isopropyl alcohol (IPA), anhydrous ethanol, and deionized (DI) water for 10 seconds each, followed by blow-drying with compressed air.
8.	The height of the silicon mold was measured using a stylus profilometer.
